    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense. one more thing, i'm seeing some really extreme values in the residuals that don't seem to follow any pattern at all. they just seem to pop up randomly and mess up the fit. is there a way to quantify just how \"abnormal\" these specific outliers are compared to the rest of the distribution?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To quantify how abnormal these specific, random outliers are, you can use standardized residual analysis or calculate Mahalanobis distance if you have multiple predictors. Standardized residuals tell you how many standard deviations away a specific point is from the regression line, providing a direct measure of abnormality. If they are drastically far outside the typical range (e.g., beyond $\\pm 3$ or $\\pm 4$ standard deviations), they are statistically significant outliers. Remember to treat these extreme points carefully, as they might represent genuine, unmodeled phenomena in the housing market.",
      "source": "target",
